159 "ARTICLE 5
160 51-3-50.
161 As used in this article, the term:
162 (1) 'Negligent security' means any claim against an owner or occupier, or against a
163 security contractor, that:
164 (A) Sounds in tort or nuisance, including, but not limited to, any claim under Article 1
165 of this chapter;
166 (B) Seeks to recover damages for bodily injury or wrongful death; and
- 7 -

25 LC 49 2233-ECS
167 (C) Arises from an alleged failure to keep persons on or around any premises safe from
168 the wrongful conduct of any third person.
169 (2) 'Owner or occupier' means any person that owns, leases, occupies, operates,
170 maintains, or manages real property of any kind or any director, officer, employee, or
171 agent of such person.
172 (3) 'Particularized warning of imminent wrongful conduct by a third person' means
173 information actually known to an owner or occupier and deemed credible by the owner
174 or occupier, which causes the owner or occupier to consciously understand that a third
175 person is likely to imminently engage in wrongful conduct on the premises that poses a
176 clear danger to the safety of persons upon the premises, such information being specific
177 as to the identity of the third person, the nature and character of the wrongful conduct, the
178 degree of dangerousness of the wrongful conduct, and the location, time, and
179 circumstances of the wrongful conduct.
180 (4) 'Premises' means the real property that is owned, leased, occupied, operated,
181 maintained, or managed by an owner or occupier.
182 (5) 'Prior occurrences of substantially similar wrongful conduct' means prior occurrences
183 of wrongful conduct which are sufficiently similar in nature and character, degree of
184 dangerousness, proximity, location, time, and circumstances to the wrongful conduct
185 from which a claim of negligent security arises to lead a reasonable person in the position
186 of the owner or occupier to apprehend that such wrongful conduct is reasonably likely to
187 occur upon the premises, to understand the risk of injury to persons upon the premises
188 presented by such wrongful conduct, and to understand that a specific and known
189 physical condition of the premises has created a risk of such wrongful conduct on the
190 premises that is substantially greater than the general risk of such wrongful conduct in the
191 vicinity of the premises.
- 8 -

