192 (6) 'Security contractor' means any person that contracts with an owner or occupier to
193 provide protective or security services upon any premises or any director, officer,
194 employee, or agent of such person.
195 (7) 'Third person' means any person other than an owner or occupier or a security
196 contractor.
197 (8) 'Wrongful conduct' means:
198 (A) Any violation of a law of this state or an ordinance of any political subdivision
199 thereof that is punishable as a felony or misdemeanor, regardless of whether such
200 violation results in an arrest, citation, accusation, indictment, or conviction; or
201 (B) Any other conduct that amounts to an intentional, or willful and wanton, tort.
202 51-3-51.
203 Except as provided in Code Section 51-3-54, an owner or occupier shall be liable for
204 negligent security arising from any injury sustained by any person upon the premises of the
205 owner or occupier as an invitee if the plaintiff proves that:
206 (1) The wrongful conduct by a third person that caused the injury sustained by the invitee
207 was reasonably foreseeable because the owner or occupier:
208 (A) Had particularized warning of imminent wrongful conduct by a third person; or
209 (B) By clear and convincing evidence, reasonably should have known that a third
210 person was reasonably likely to engage in such wrongful conduct upon the premises,
211 based on:
212 (i) Prior occurrences of substantially similar wrongful conduct upon the premises of
213 which the owner or occupier knew;
214 (ii) Prior occurrences of substantially similar wrongful conduct upon the property
215 adjoining the premises, or otherwise occurring within 500 yards of the premises, of
216 which the owner or occupier knew; or
- 9 -

